<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Tutamun:
[I]A place in the credits? Wow, thanx. Yes, sure I want to be in there [!]  :)  :D
***
If the AI thing is done right and the game is fun, everybody will say boah! this game is cool. (Even the game magazines.) And then the game will sell.
Half Life was the first game I know that had inteligent opponents. And that was fun. (I don't know any other (real time) game with good AI. Even if they said the AI is good; it wasn't.)
If your opponents behave like in real world it will not be to frustrating since you expect them to do these things. If they don't do what you expect from them then you will say: "stupid program". (It's not that I don't want anything surprising like an ambush. It's rather that afterwars you should say: "I should have expected this, since they are really smart.")

Game balance: &gt;&gt;You also get to deal with coordinated effort, and it can be quite painful. (I had to make the skeletons weaker after I implemented it, that's how good it works[...]&lt;&lt;
Strong critters will not need to use something like the hit in the back tactic, but for weaker ones it is vital for their survival. It should always make sense.

Another thing on animals:
If you get near the lair or its babys it will get more agressive (eg. use a different tactic) than normaly.

Tiny little detail: (making the world come alive)
A snake lying in the sun will disapear in high grass or a hole in the ground if it hears/feels your footsteps.
A flock of birds fly away when you come near them, making lots of noise. (An inteligent opponent may be warned of your comming by this. He knows that someone is sneaking through the wood and may come and look who it is.)
If you come to a safe place, there could be a rabit sitting in the grass. When you come it looks up and then hops away.
In a town children run around laughing and playing whatever they used to play before computers were invented.  ;)
Trees shaking in the wind. A few leaves could be blown over the ground. Rain could come from different directions.
But don't overdo this. The screen should not be crowded with insects, bugs  ;), and other moving stuff. This stuff is nice for the atmosphere but it should not distract from the game. Ants/Flies for example are everywhere, but you should not see them in the game unless they are needed (ie. If you find a dead person there could be lots of flies buzzing around, since this enhances the atmosphere).

On the book/diary thing:
At least the things you have acomplished and the things you still have to do should be recorded in a book. This makes it easier to "remember" what you were up to, if you stopped playing for a week or two.[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
</td></tr>
